C lets you define variables with block scope:<p><pre><code>  int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
  	for(int i=0;i<10;++i)
  		printf("%d
", i);
  	printf("%d
", i);
  }
</code></pre>
The last line fails to compile'i' is no longer defined after exiting the loop.<p>Java:<p><pre><code>  public static void main(String[] args) {
  	for(int i=0;i<10;++i)
  		System.out.println(i);
  	System.out.println(i);
  }
</code></pre>
That also won't compile.<p>Coming from a language that supports variables with block scope, PHP's behavior is very surprising indeed. If the first mention of $object is in the loop, I can understand someone expecting $object in the second loop to be a distinct variable that just happens to share the same name.<p>This behavior is even surprising coming from Perl, though for a slightly different reason:<p><pre><code>  @array = ('c', 'c++', 'java', 'perl');
  foreach $item (@array) {
      if($item eq 'perl') {
          $item = 'php';
      }
  }
  foreach $item (@array) {
      print $item . "
";
  }
</code></pre>
For that matter, PHP's reference semantics are a little surprising in general coming from any other language I've ever used.
